The Telegraph - Calcutta (Kolkata) | Business | ITC earnings up 16%
                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                       ITC earnings up 16%
          OUR SPECIAL CORRESPONDENT                          Standing tall                                  
	Calcutta, May 23: ITC Ltd has posted a profit after tax of Rs 3,120.1 crore for the year ended March 31, 2008, against Rs 2,699.97 crore in the previous year, a rise of 15.6 per cent.        
	Net sales stood at Rs 13,947.53 crore compared with Rs 12,164 crore a year ago.        
	The companys topline was driven by its non-tobacco business  ITCs focus for the past few years.         
	However, its profitability continued to depend on its tobacco products.        
	The ITC board has recommended a dividend of Rs 3.50 for each share of Re 1.        
	Net sales for the quarter ended March 31 stood at Rs 3,934.39 crore against Rs 3,371.86 crore, registering a growth rate of 16.7 per cent.        
	Profit before tax for the reporting quarter rose 15.3 per cent to Rs 1,084 crore from Rs 940.43 crore in the corresponding quarter of the previous year.         
	Profit after tax was Rs 735.64 crore in the period under review compared with Rs 650.69 crore a year ago.        
	Profit from cigarettes grew 14 per cent to Rs 3,634 crore in 2007-08 from Rs 3,172 crore in 2006-07.        
	On a like-to-like basis, profit before tax from the companys hotel business rose to Rs 410.77 crore from Rs 350.78 crore.        
	Profit before tax from the paper business stood at Rs 453.14 crore compared with Rs 416.78 crore.        
	Agri-business profitability was Rs 129 crore compared with Rs 123.55 crore a year ago.        
	Non-tobacco FMCG items such as food, garments and personal care products continued to be a drag on the bottomline with losses mounting to Rs 263.52 crore compared with Rs 201.99 crore in the previous year.                                                                                                                                                       
